Next, let's proceed with the computation of accounting break-even in various scenarios.


1. Accounting break-even when the variable cost is $2,135 per unit.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Accounting break-even point} 
&=\left(\dfrac{{\$8,100,000}+{\$3,100,000}}{{\$2,980}-{\$2,135}}\right)
\\[10pt]
&=\dfrac{{\$11,200,000}}{{\$845}}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{13,254\text{ units}}
\end{aligned}$$


**As presented above, the accounting break-even point is 13,254 units when the variable cost is $2,135 per unit.**

2. Accounting break-even when the variable cost is $41 per unit.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Accounting break-even point} 
&=\left(\dfrac{{\$185,000}+{\$183,000}}{{\$46}-{\$41}}\right)
\\[10pt]
&=\dfrac{{\$368,000}}{{\$5}}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{73,600\text{ units}}
\end{aligned}$$

**As seen above, the accounting break-even point is 73,600 units when the variable cost is $41 per unit.**

3. Accounting break-even when the variable cost is $3 per unit.


$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Accounting break-even point}
&=\left(\dfrac{{\$2,770}+{\$1,050}}{{\$9}-{\$3}}\right)
\\[10pt]
&=\dfrac{{\$3,820}}{{\$6}}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{637\text{ units}}
\end{aligned}$$

**As shown above, the accounting break-even point is 637 units when the variable cost is $3 per unit.**
